observations.recommendation:
We recommended that Local Chief Executive (LCE) to require the:

Municipal Accountant and Municipal General Services Officer (MGSO)-designate to continue and prioritize the reconciliation of PPE balances recorded per GL and per RPCPPE. Additionally, to avail of the one-time cleansing of PPE as provided in COA Circular No. 2020-006; 

Municipal Accountant to prepare the necessary adjustments to record as prior period adjustments the prior years’ PPE acquisition below ₱50,000.00 that are still recorded as PPE;

Municipal Engineer to provide the Municipal Accountant with the necessary documents relative to the demolished/destroyed buildings and other structures; and

Municipal Accountant to prepare the necessary adjustments to derecognize from the books the demolished/destroyed buildings upon receipt of the necessary documents provided by the Municipal Engineer.

We recommended that LCE to instruct the:

Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer to prioritize the regular and periodic reconciliation of the CIB balances per books and cashbook records to attain correct reporting of the account’s balance in the FS;

Municipal Accountant to prepare the necessary Journal Entry Vouchers (JEV) to record the identified book reconciling items and to investigate those that are unidentified. Similarly, to ensure that all identified book reconciling items in the monthly BRS are immediately adjusted in the books;

Municipal Accountant to ensure that monthly BRS for all bank accounts are prepared. If Bank Statements cannot be obtained, avail of/request alternative verified bank records as basis for the BRS preparation; and

Municipal Accountant and Municipal Treasurer to coordinate and conduct a thorough review of records to determine the validity of the stale checks, confirm cancellation thereof, and make the necessary adjustments.

We recommended and Management agreed to:
Review the existing practices in conducting physical count of its PPE and direct the IC to conduct a proper and complete physical count of all PPE and submit the RPCPPE within the deadline set by MNGAS for LGUs;
Direct the Municipal Accountant (MA) and MGSO to maintain complete and proper accounting and property records relative to PPE items;
Establish an appraisal and disposal committee which will be responsible in the disposal process of unserviceable PPE items;
Formally transfer ownership by donating PPE items which were intentionally acquired for the benefit of other LGUs; and
Require the IC, MGSO, and MA to present PPE additions, improvements, or major rehabilitations in their main PPE account in the RPCPPE, PCs, and PPELCs.

We reiterated our prior year’s recommendation and the LCE agreed to instruct the:
MA and the Municipal Treasurer (MT) to prioritize the regular and periodic reconciliation of the CIB balances per books and cashbook to attain correct reporting of the account’s balance in the FS;
MA to prepare the necessary Journal Entry Vouchers to record the identified book reconciling items and to investigate those that are unidentified. Similarly, to ensure that all identified book reconciling items in the monthly BRS are immediately adjusted in the books;
MA to ensure that monthly BRS for all bank accounts are prepared. If Bank Statements cannot be obtained, avail of/request alternative verified bank records as basis for the BRS preparation; and
MA and MT to coordinate and conduct a thorough review of records to determine the validity of the stale checks, confirm cancellation thereof, and make the necessary adjustments.

We recommended and the Management agreed to:
Consider establishing a stockroom to enable the MGSO to effectively facilitate centralized monitoring of the procurement, issuance, and balances of all inventory items by maintaining accurate SCs;
Direct the IC to conduct complete physical count of all inventories in accordance with the prescribed rules;
Require the MA to record inventory using the prescribed perpetual inventory method to ensure reliability and accuracy of the accounts presented in the FS. Also, require the MA to maintain SLCs in compliance with aforementioned guidelines; and
Conduct regular reconciliation of the SLCs and SCs to ensure that all purchases and issuances are properly accounted for.

We recommended and Management agreed to:
Prioritize filling vacant plantilla positions and, when necessary, utilize casual or emergency staff hiring practices in accordance with CSC guidelines and other relevant rule and regulations;
Review existing HRP and staffing pattern to reflect the actual necessity in outsourced manpower and properly incorporate them in the budgeting process;
Invite all concerned department heads and key LGU employees to fully comply with EO No. 27 of 2022, or the internal policy for hiring JO/COS in the Municipality to provide clear guidelines and controls over the hiring of JO/COS personnel; and
Discontinue the hiring of JO personnel for functions that are expected to be accomplished by permanent positions, especially those functions that require custody of any government funds or property.

We recommended and the LCE agreed to:
Instruct the MA and the MT to conduct periodic reconciliation of their cash records to come up with the correct balances of CIB – LCCA to be presented in the FS;
Direct the MA to exert extra effort and obtain the necessary documents needed to support the identified reconciling items and draw JEV to record all valid reconciling items that require adjustment/correction in the books;
Direct the MA and MT to investigate the validity of long outstanding DIT by reviewing past records and conferring with concerned AGDBs;
Require the MT to cancel the stale checks, report these in the RCI and return the same together with original vouchers, if any, to the MA who shall prepare the JEV to record the necessary adjustments; and
Instruct the MA to communicate immediately to the concerned AGDBs any errors committed by the bank which were identified during the preparation of the BRS for correction.

We recommended and the LCE agreed to require the MT and the MA to submit to the LSB the following reports to be used as basis for the SEF budget of the ensuing year strictly not later than July 15 of the current year:
Actual SEF Income for the immediately preceding fiscal year;
Actual SEF Income for the first two quarters of the current year;
The estimated SEF income for the last two quarters of the current year; and
The annual estimates for the ensuing year.
We likewise recommended that the LSB observe the timely preparation, submission and approval of the Annual SEF Budget as prescribed by DepEd-DBM-DILG JC No. 1, series of 2017.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor/Treasurer strategize how to efficiently and effectively collect taxes and consider, among others, the following measures:
Conduct information and education campaign/activities, e.g. social media/radio, and other means of communication to encourage land owners to pay regularly their tax obligation and the benefits of paying early or on time.
Issue letters of demand to delinquent taxpayers with information on the possible consequences for non-payment of taxes;
Develop collection strategies to enhance collection of taxes like seeking the assistance of barangay officials in the house-to house campaign;
Post the notice of delinquency appertaining to the payment of real property tax in the main entrance of the municipal building and other conspicuous public places frequently visited by people;
Prepare the list of all delinquent real property taxes and submit the same to the Sangguniang Bayan with a request for assistance in the enforcement of the remedies for collection of those taxes; and
Avail of the remedies by administrative action thru levy on real property or by judicial action.

We recommended that Management:
Require the drivers to indicate the odometer reading in the DTT, and if odometer is out of order, require the supply officer to request for its immediate repair or replacement in order to determine the actual gasoline consumption;
Require the accomplishment of DTT on every travel;
Set guidelines on the limitation of gasoline consumption; and
Require the submission of Monthly Report of Official Travels and Monthly Reports of Fuel Consumptions to the Office of the Auditor.

